WEBVTT

00:08.380 --> 00:12.320
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.720 --> 00:34.020
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:34.020 --> 00:38.340
And here are your hosts.

00:51.540 --> 00:56.340
Although he appeared in print for the first time in 1969 with a short story in the Science

00:56.340 --> 01:01.320
Fiction Magazine Galaxy, Haldeman gained tremendous popularity when he came out with his multi-award

01:01.320 --> 01:03.020
winning novel, The Forever War.

01:03.380 --> 01:08.300
The novel was serialized in astounding science fiction, starting in 1972, then released as

01:08.300 --> 01:09.380
a book in 1974.

01:10.100 --> 01:14.420
The Forever War is similar to Robert Heinlein's book Starship Troopers, in that both have

01:14.420 --> 01:18.380
intergalactic war, powered body armor, and highly advanced weapons as common elements.

01:19.060 --> 01:22.040
Differences between the books show up in the way the authors treat war.

01:22.540 --> 01:27.460
Heinlein's conflict was sort of a John Wayne-style battle with the bad guys, whereas Haldeman's

01:27.460 --> 01:31.220
dealt with the emotions and reactions of his characters to the war they fought.

01:31.220 --> 01:33.540
We asked Haldeman if the resemblance was intentional.

02:02.420 --> 02:11.580
But no, if there is any relation to any book, it is to my own first novel, War Year, because

02:11.580 --> 02:18.180
it's an expansion into a science fiction universe of the notions that I was trying to express

02:18.180 --> 02:21.100
in mainstream novel.

02:39.400 --> 02:44.180
Haldeman has a background in physics and astronomy, and told us about how he uses his hard science

02:44.180 --> 02:45.340
background in his work.

02:46.340 --> 02:52.520
Well, I try to use it to make the worlds that are in the event more believable, at least

02:52.520 --> 02:56.860
to me, since I do have a background in science and engineering.

02:56.860 --> 03:03.140
I think, well, the writer has to at least suspend his own disbelief while he's making

03:03.140 --> 03:07.760
up these stories, and it's easier for me to do it if it's on a fairly solid scientific

03:07.760 --> 03:08.460
foundation.

03:09.460 --> 03:15.680
Even though my science is rather old fashioned and probably rather sloppy by our real scientists'

03:16.300 --> 03:21.600
standards, it's still enough to convince me, so it's fulfilled its function.

03:28.940 --> 03:32.840
In the Forever War, the soldiers experience time dilation when they travel to and from

03:32.840 --> 03:33.520
the war zone.

03:34.060 --> 03:38.240
That means that due to the tremendous velocity of their spaceships, dozens of years have passed

03:38.240 --> 03:41.880
on Earth, while only a few months have passed for the soldiers on the spaceships.

03:42.420 --> 03:46.500
Haldeman told us how he used hard science to evoke some of the feeling the soldiers have.

03:47.660 --> 03:54.560
It goes deeper than just description, the time dilation in the Forever War.

03:55.110 --> 03:56.800
It's scientifically accurate.

03:56.940 --> 04:05.440
Its main function is metaphorical, and that is to demonstrate how the soldiers who fight

04:05.440 --> 04:09.220
a war become isolated from the culture that they're supposed to be protecting.

04:10.200 --> 04:16.460
It's using a science-fictional device to exaggerate something that happens to every soldier.

04:18.000 --> 04:23.460
I remember when I came back from Vietnam, I was suddenly plunged into what was an alien

04:23.460 --> 04:26.720
culture, even though I'd only been a soldier for two years.

04:28.060 --> 04:29.400
A lot of things had changed.

04:31.200 --> 04:37.440
It's not a great thing to come back, there were no victory parades and that sort of thing.

04:44.320 --> 04:44.860
It's a great thing to come back to.

04:49.560 --> 04:52.740
Join us next time when we continue our interview with Joe Haldeman.

05:00.280 --> 05:05.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

05:05.000 --> 05:08.800
Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

05:55.980 --> 05:59.840
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:15.640 --> 06:20.940
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:23.560 --> 06:25.240
And here are your hosts.

06:30.440 --> 06:34.100
This is David Carson and David Cruz.

06:34.580 --> 06:38.080
Today we'll be continuing our interview with author Joe Haldeman. It was mentioned in the

06:38.080 --> 06:42.640
previous program that Haldeman served in Vietnam and uses that experience in some of his stories.

06:43.340 --> 06:47.360
For instance, in one of his stories, he tells of a soldier who is severely hurt by a laser

06:47.360 --> 06:50.840
mine. We asked Haldeman if that was drawn from his own experiences.

06:51.940 --> 06:58.720
Well, I was wounded pretty severely in Vietnam. I was hospitalized for six months and it was

06:58.720 --> 07:04.380
a boog-o-trap. I didn't set it off, somebody else did, but it was a pretty big one. I had

07:04.380 --> 07:11.240
over 200 separate wounds, but managed to come out of it all right after a few months of

07:11.820 --> 07:19.140
physical therapy. So, yeah, I draw on that experience. The one you're talking about is

07:19.140 --> 07:25.460
a mind of his own. But I think I've got other short stories like the private war, private

07:25.460 --> 07:32.000
jaco, the draw on that memory. We wondered if he was exercising demons by writing about

07:32.000 --> 07:39.240
that experience. I don't know whether I am or not. I think I'm just using available material.

07:40.840 --> 07:45.500
I don't think the demon is too easily exercised by fiction.

07:46.760 --> 07:50.480
We asked if being in Vietnam had any other effects on his writing.

07:51.480 --> 08:00.320
Being in the army had an important effect on my writing, aside from war, because I met a whole new

08:00.320 --> 08:09.000
class of people. That is all of my friends while I was growing up tended to be white, middle

08:09.000 --> 08:15.460
class, upper middle class kids. There were successors, white, middle class, upper class

08:16.200 --> 08:24.300
scientists, so forth. It was just a mundane revelation to find that people who came from

08:24.300 --> 08:30.660
different backgrounds still had an awful lot in common with me. Most of the guys in my

08:30.660 --> 08:38.120
combat outfit were urban black high school or junior high school dropouts. They got along

08:38.120 --> 08:43.300
quite well. Haldeman has written two novels and edited one anthology, all dealing with

08:43.300 --> 08:47.980
war, but by no means should you consider him just a writer of war stories. That's right,

08:48.100 --> 08:51.780
he writes about what happens to people who are placed in that type of violent situation.

08:52.680 --> 08:57.100
He seems to be exploring what makes his characters tick more than the situations surrounding

08:57.100 --> 09:02.200
the characters. One of the themes in his work is man or mankind being changed when facing

09:02.200 --> 09:04.520
conflict. We ask Haldeman to respond to that.

09:05.720 --> 09:12.960
I think it's obvious that confronting death on a daily basis changes people, sometimes

09:12.960 --> 09:21.380
radically for the worse, and that people who are totally dehumanized by war. But speaking

09:21.380 --> 09:27.340
racially, I don't think you could make such a broad statement. What's behind some of the

09:27.340 --> 09:32.220
things I'm writing is the hope that human nature eventually may improve to the point

09:32.220 --> 09:37.820
where we won't have wars. We can find other ways to settle our differences.

09:39.280 --> 09:44.280
In his novel All My Sins Remembered, the main character is red-taped and shuffled into doing

09:44.280 --> 09:48.820
something that he is diametrically opposed to. When he rebels against the situation, he

09:48.820 --> 09:56.760
is terminated. The story is about a bureaucracy that totally takes over a man's identity,

09:57.100 --> 10:02.600
and he doesn't really exist except as a tool for that bureaucracy. When he becomes an

10:02.600 --> 10:08.160
efficient tool, he's scrapped. The main character ends up being a spy for the government and

10:08.160 --> 10:15.240
carrying out covert operations for them. And he does them more or less against his will,

10:15.240 --> 10:22.300
that is to say, through very advanced techniques of conditioning. He's turned into a thoroughly

10:22.300 --> 10:29.400
different person. He was a Buddhist, a pacifist when he started out. He did not get the job

10:29.400 --> 10:33.880
he signed up for. They twisted him around into being a killing machine.

10:35.440 --> 10:40.460
If all this makes Haldeman sound like a pessimist, well, he's not that either. Join us next time

10:40.460 --> 10:42.360
when we find out more about Joe Haldeman.

10:49.800 --> 10:55.280
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association

10:55.280 --> 10:58.440
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

11:58.640 --> 12:04.500
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:07.140 --> 12:08.760
And here are your hosts.

12:13.660 --> 12:19.240
This is David Carson and David Cruz. Today we continue our interview with author Joe Haldeman.

12:19.880 --> 12:24.260
So far in our conversation with Haldeman, we've discussed how he used his experiences in Vietnam

12:24.260 --> 12:28.440
in his writing and some of his early works. Now we're going to look at his writing style

12:28.440 --> 12:33.580
in two particular stories. A short story to Howard Hughes' A Modest Proposal and a novel,

12:34.100 --> 12:39.380
Mindbridge. Haldeman tells these stories by using narratives by the main characters in the stories,

12:39.380 --> 12:44.480
reports by them and others, portions of books written long after the time set in the story

12:44.480 --> 12:49.860
and other non-standard writing techniques. We asked him if he got the ideas for this type of style

12:49.860 --> 12:52.060
when he was attending the Iowa Writers Conference.

12:53.160 --> 12:57.220
Oh, not really. The connection is with John Doe's process, actually.

12:58.660 --> 13:06.020
I read the U.S. H. Relate some years before at Mindbridge and really was impressed by the way it worked

13:06.020 --> 13:12.380
and thought it would work really well in science fiction. So I tried it out in a rather long short story

13:12.380 --> 13:20.420
to Howard Hughes' A Modest Proposal. And it looked like it would work, so I went ahead and applied it to Mindbridge.

13:22.160 --> 13:26.960
I did do most of that book while I was studying at Iowa, and that's why I had the dedication.

13:28.620 --> 13:32.740
The authors at the Iowa Writers Conference were, for the most part, not science fiction writers.

13:32.740 --> 13:36.180
We asked Haldeman about their reaction to his being a science fiction author.

13:37.220 --> 13:43.320
Well, they were a little apprehensive about it. See, they didn't know I was a science fiction writer when I joined the workshop.

13:44.220 --> 13:48.540
So I joined on the basis of my first novel, which was not science fiction.

13:49.700 --> 13:55.220
And some of them were outwardly hostile towards science fiction, such as Stanley Elkin.

13:55.220 --> 14:00.700
Others were anywhere between apprehensive and slightly sympathetic.

14:01.420 --> 14:07.140
Stephen Becker, one of them, had actually had a few pieces in the magazine Fantasy and Science Fiction.

14:08.220 --> 14:19.960
In general, though, they thinly disguised the attitude that the stuff was just commercial fiction, and therefore beneath contempt.

14:21.620 --> 14:26.020
That's an attitude I've never understood. Some of the world's finest literature is science fiction.

14:26.640 --> 14:29.140
We asked Haldeman what he thought about that type of attitude.

14:30.240 --> 14:38.840
But the field is judged by its worst, not by its best. And people like that think of science fiction.

14:39.020 --> 14:46.520
They think in terms of great D-movies and Lazy Television. They've never read much of the best of the field.

14:52.860 --> 14:57.060
Using science fiction is possible to consider various aspects of mankind's future.

14:57.700 --> 15:00.680
And science fiction is the only literary form to speculate about the future.

15:01.240 --> 15:04.740
We asked Haldeman if he thought that mankind might be radically different in the future.

15:06.040 --> 15:10.520
I think it's quite possible, even say within the span of a century,

15:10.520 --> 15:17.240
so many of the things that determine human nature are things that can be mitigated by technology.

15:19.080 --> 15:24.520
Such as the problem of dying so soon.

15:25.380 --> 15:35.540
That is, it's possible that in a couple of generations, a century, two centuries, maybe a thousand years, maybe as long as we care to,

15:35.540 --> 15:41.700
that will radically change human nature because it will take the pressure off of individuals.

15:44.800 --> 15:57.400
The other or other less sanguine notions is possible that sciences and communication will grow into a kind of sophisticated mind control.

15:58.840 --> 16:05.300
It will be difficult for the individual to know exactly what is his idea and what has been induced by his own society.

16:06.620 --> 16:11.480
Sort of a sophisticated life-long brainwashing doesn't seem too unlikely.

16:12.540 --> 16:14.400
And you can argue that it's happening now.

16:16.180 --> 16:21.700
Join us next time when we wrap up our interview with Joe Haldeman and find out how he got involved with Star Trek.

